05818nam a22006495i 9780814769447DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t19941994nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147694477 a10.18574/97808147694472doi  a(DE-B1597)546920  a(OCoLC)906965261  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aSOC0120002bisacsh04a306.76/622000aQueer Words, Queer Images :bCommunication and the Construction of Homosexuality /cRonald Jeffrey Ringer. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[1994] 4c©1994  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Logic of Folly in the Political Campaigns of Harvey Milk -- t2. On the Owning of Words: Reflections on San Francisco Arts and Athletics vs. United States Olympic Committee -- t3. Die Non: Gay Liberation and the Rhetoric of Pure Tolerance -- t4. Reflections on Gay and Lesbian Rhetoric -- t5. Guilt by Association: Homosexuality and AIDS on Prime-Time Television -- t6. Whose Desire? Lesbian (Non)Sexuality and Television's Perpetuation of Hetero/Sexism -- t7. Old Strategies for New Texts: How American Television Is Creating and Treating Lesbian Characters -- t8. What Is Wrong with This Picture? Lesbian Women and Gay Men on Television -- t9. A Portrait of the Adolescent as a Young Gay: The Politics of Male Homosexuality in Young Adult Fiction -- t10. Self as Other: The Politics of Identity in the Works of Edmund White -- t11. Female Athlete = Lesbian: A Myth Constructed from Gendex Role Expectations and Lesbiphobia -- t12. The Politics of Self and Other -- t13. Self-Disclosure Behaviors of the Stigmatized: Strategies and Outcomes for the Revelation of Sexual Orientation -- t14. Gender and Relationship Crises: Contrasting Reasons, Responses, and Relational Orientations -- t15. Gay and Lesbian Couple Relationships -- t16. Reflections on Interpersonal Communication in Gay and Lesbian Relationships -- t17. Performing the (Lesbian) Self: Teacher as Text -- t18. Coming Out to Students: Notes from the College Classroom -- t19. Coming Out in the Classroom: Faculty Disclosures of Sexuality -- t20. Ways of Coming Out in the Classroom -- tContributors -- tName Index -- tSubject Index 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn many arenas the debate is raging over the nature of sexual orientation. Queer Words, Queer Images addresses this debate, but with a difference, arguing that homosexuality has become an issue precisely because of the way in which we discuss, debate, and communicate about the concept and experience of homosexuality. The debate over homosexuality is fundamentally an issue of communication-as we can see by the recent controversy over gays in the military. This controversy, termed by one gay man as the annoying habit of heterosexual men to overestimate their own attractiveness, has been debated in communication-sensitive terms, such as morale and discipline. The twenty chapters address such subjects as gay political language, homosexuality and AIDS on prime-time television, the politics of male homosexuality in young adult fiction, the identification of female athleticism with lesbianism, the politics of identity in the works of Edmund White, and coming out strategies. This is must reading for students of communication practices and theory, and for everyone interested in human sexuality. Contributing to the book are: James Chesebro (Indiana State), James Darsey (Ohio State), Joseph A. Devito (Hunter College, CUNY), Timothy Edgar (Purdue), Mary Anne Fitzpatrick (Wisconsin, Madison), Karen A. Foss (Humboldt State), Kirk Fuoss (St. Lawrence), Larry Gross (Pennsylvania), Darlene Hantzis (Indiana State), Fred E. Jandt (California State, San Bernardino), Mercilee Jenkins (San Francisco State), Valerie Lehr (St. Lawrence), Lynn C. Miller (T